            <!-- Contents -->
            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">One of Ibn ʿArabī’s most important minor treatises, this work deals with the fundamental premises of his metaphysics; the Divine Essence and Attributes, the human being as the intermediary between Creator and Creation, and the author’s conception of the Universal Reality (al-haqīqa al-kulliya). Built around a pronounced philosophical framework, almost in the kalām style, and copiously illustrated with diagrams and tables. (Fenton and Gloton).</note>
               <note type="structure">Structure of Work</note>
               <note type="contentsNote">Note on Contents</note>
            </noteGrp>
            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">A much copied work, verified by two historic mss.: Manisa 1183 (655H taken from al-Ḥabashī’s copy), and Veliyuddin 1686 (c.667 and copied by disciple of SQ’s). We know from its mention in al-Tadbīrāt al-Ilāhīya (see Elmore JMIAS 29) that this was one of the first works IA began, but the surviving versions are later, probably written in Tunis in 598/1202 at the home of al-Mahdawī (see FM. Chapter 4).</note>
